	</div><div class="blogs_entrybody" style="clear:both">
		The sixth document appeared to be an 'open issues' list with Treesoft's next big title called "GLOOM".  John motioned to me to pass the document to him."This is amazing.  Our dirty laundry is getting aired out in the backyard of the internet." John said with an apathetic sigh.<br/><br/>"John, have you or any other member of the management team interviewed your employees regarding the documents?  Perhaps a disgruntled employee is slowly releasing these documents in an effort to draw attention to problems within the company?" I asked.<br/><br/>John looked like I had called his mother a moose.<br/><br/>"That's ridiculous!  We have a pretty tight-knit group here.  If there were internal issues, someone would bring them to my attention.  We are very employee friendly here.  What hurts one of us hurts all of us." John said in a harsh tone.<br/><br/>Scrap and I excused ourselves from the meeting after discussing some logistical issues with the management team and retreated to the conference room to grab our stowed gear.<br/><br/>"All we need now is a tent." Scrap joked as he unpacked our equipment bags in the last remaining empty office at Treesoft.  John had arranged for us to set up shop in an office near the development team.<br/><br/>Our first goal in this investigation was to isolate and contain the breach, if it existed.  Scrap had provided me with a diagram of the Treesoft network to assist in my planning.<br/><br/>"According to this diagram, this network is very simple.  There is a single connection to the internet via a high speed DSL connection.  There is one router, one firewall, and a single core ethernet switch with multiple ethernet blades." I said as I traced my finger along the surface of the Visio document.<br/><br/>Scrap passed me another piece of paper filled with his monkey-scratch scribbling.  "Correct, and they are using a NAT scenario to route two RFC-1918 address spaces; 10.0.1.0 and 10.0.2.0.  All servers and a few workstations have static addresses on 10.0.1.1-10.0.1.128, and 10.0.1.129-10.0.1.254 and all of 10.0.2.0 appear to be DHCP."<br/><br/>"Alright, Scrap.  We're closing the 'net' from the outside to the inside.  What's your suggested plan of action?" I asked, testing Scrap's knowledge of our established procedures.<br/><br/>"First, I'm finding out what that attractive girl's name is that brought Peter that sixth document a few minutes ago.  Secondly, I'm going to get her phone number.  Thirdly, I'm going to ..." <br/><br/>"Scrap." I said, cutting him off in mid-sentence.  "The network."<br/><br/>Scrap regained his composure.  "Oh, right.  The network.  Locate all points of egress and ingress, attach a capture box to each point, assess the security of those points with the usual tools.  Work backwards from the internet into the network, device by device.  Sound like a plan?" <br/><br/>"Correct.  We need to go all the way back and hit every server, network device, workstation... basically everything with an IP address.  Then what?" I queried.<br/><br/>"I reverse direction, and work from the inside to the outside.  What is this, a quiz?" Scrap snapped back as he emptied the last of our equipment bags.<br/><br/>"Just a refresher.  I'm going to start my examination of the documents and perform the employee interviews.  If you forget how to use nmap, just give me a call." I said with a grin.<br/><br/>Scrap wasn't amused.<br/><br/>I wandered over to the employee break room with my Powerbook and spied a fresh pot of coffee brewing.  <br/><br/>"What timing." I joked as I poured a fresh cup of coffee into a nearby styrofoam cup.<br/><br/>I opened up the lid to my Powerbook, entered my password and my desktop sprang to life.  Peter had mentioned to me earlier that his assistant, Chandra, would be emailing a zip file containing all six documents.   I appreciated that, but I wanted to grab the documents directly from the FFS site. <br/><br/>I scored a break room table near a wall which had an easily accessible network connection marked "Employee Use Only".  Ed had given us permission to attach whatever devices were necessary to complete this investigation, and by Joe my Powerbook was one of those devices.  <br/><br/>After receiving a 10.0.2.x IP address from the network, I was able to access the internet.<br/><br/>"Ok, so I'm a nosey customer, and I want to research Treesoft.  Hello, Google!" I said to myself as my copy of Firefox appeared.  I typed in "Treesoft" into the Google search field and immediately received several thousand hits.  Most of the search returns were web pages from Treesoft's own website, game review sites, game retailers, and discussion boards.  <br/><br/>Thirty minutes later, I saw them.<p><hr><table width="100%" bgcolor="#FFFFCC" cellpadding="9px">
